sections.markdown: An **Infrastructure Monitoring** Dashboard provides a unified view of system health across servers, networks, and applications. It tracks key metrics such as CPU, memory, disk, and network utilization in real time. Alerts and thresholds help detect bottlenecks or failures early. Visual insights through graphs and heatmaps enable quick root cause analysis. This dashboard ensures optimal uptime, performance, and resource efficiency across the IT landscape.[DT URLï»¿](https://dynatrace.com)

metrics.description: Shows percentage of memory currently used. Used memory is calculated by OneAgent as follows: used = total - available. So the used memory metric displayed in Dynatrace analysis views is not equal to the used memory metric displayed by system tools. At the same time, it's important to remember that system tools report used memory the way they do due to historical reasons, and that this particular method of calculating used memory isn't really representative of how the Linux kernel manages memory in modern systems. The difference in these measurements is in fact quite significant, too. Note: Calculated by taking 100% - "Memory available %".

grail.canonicalQuery:
fetch spans, from:-30m, to:now(), scanLimitGBytes:500
| filter span.kind == "client" AND isNotNull(http.request.method)
| lookup [fetch dt.entity.service], sourceField:dt.entity.service, lookupField:id, fields:{service.name = entity.name}
| summarize by:{service.name, http.request.method, url.full}, http_spans = count()
| sort http_spans desc
| limit 100
| fieldsRemove url.full
